<doc id="485424" wikidata="Q304490" url="?curid=485424" title="Householder transformation">
<text>In linear algebra, a Householder transformation (also known as a Householder reflection or elementary reflector) is a linear transformation that describes a reflection about a plane or hyperplane containing the origin. The Householder transformation was used in a 1958 paper by Alston Scott Householder.

Its analogue over general inner product spaces is the Householder operator.

==Definition==

===Transformation===

The reflection hyperplane can be defined by its &quot;normal vector&quot;, a unit vector formula_1 (a vector with length formula_2) that is orthogonal to the hyperplane. The reflection of a point formula_3 about this hyperplane is the linear transformation:

: formula_4

where formula_1 is given as a column unit vector with conjugate transpose formula_6, and considering formula_7 as a vector from the origin to the point formula_8.

===Householder matrix===

The matrix constructed from this transformation can be expressed in terms of an outer product as:

: formula_9

is known as the Householder matrix, where formula_10 is the identity matrix.

====Properties====

The Householder matrix has the following properties:
* it is Hermitian: formula_11,
* it is unitary: formula_12 (via the Sherman-Morrison formula),
* hence it is involutory: formula_13.
* A Householder matrix has eigenvalues formula_14. To see this, notice that if formula_15 is orthogonal to the vector formula_1 which was used to create the reflector, then formula_17, i.e., formula_2 is an eigenvalue of multiplicity formula_19, since there are formula_19 independent vectors orthogonal to formula_1. Also, notice formula_22 (since formula_23 is by definition a unit vector), and so formula_24 is an eigenvalue with multiplicity formula_2.
* The determinant of a Householder reflector is formula_24, since the determinant of a matrix is the product of its eigenvalues, in this case one of which is formula_24 with the remainder being formula_2 (as in the previous point), or via the Matrix determinant lemma.

====Example====

consider the normalization of a vector of 1&#x27;s 

formula_29

Then the Householder matrix corresponding to this vector is

formula_30

formula_31

formula_32

formula_33

Note that if we have a vector representing a coordinate in the 2D plane

formula_34

Then in this case formula_35 flips and negates the x and y coordinates, in other words

formula_36

Which corresponds to reflecting the vector across the line formula_37, which our original vector formula_38 is normal to.

==Applications==

===Geometric optics===

In geometric optics, specular reflection can be expressed in terms of the Householder matrix (see &quot;&quot;).

===Numerical linear algebra===

Householder transformations are widely used in numerical linear algebra, for example, to annihilate the entries below the main diagonal of a matrix, to perform QR decompositions and in the first step of the QR algorithm. They are also widely used for transforming to a Hessenberg form. For symmetric or Hermitian matrices, the symmetry can be preserved, resulting in tridiagonalization.

====QR decomposition====

